        "desc1eng": "Debus, a martial art and cultural form, originated from Banten, Indonesia, and has become an integral part of the rich cultural heritage in the region. With deep historical roots, Debus combines spiritual elements, performing arts, and martial skills, creating a unique and fascinating heritage. Debus is a traditional martial art passed down from generation to generation in Banten society. Although its exact origins cannot be definitively traced, this martial art has been a significant part of Bantenese life for centuries. Essentially, Debus involves physical performances that blend strength, agility, and bodily endurance with mystical and spiritual elements. A distinctive feature of Debus is the use of various sharp objects, such as knives, shards of glass, or bamboo, which practitioners use to demonstrate their toughness and bravery. It's not just an ordinary physical performance; it reflects inner strength, self-control, and belief in spiritual power. Debus artists believe that by mastering this art, they can build a connection with the spirit world and protect themselves from harm.",
        "desc2eng": "Uniquely, Debus serves not only as a martial art but also as an entertaining art form. Debus performances often involve spectacular acts such as piercing the body with sharp objects without causing harm or combining dance with martial movements. This creates an extraordinary visual and sensory experience for the audience while maintaining the spiritual and philosophical aspects of the art. The mystical and spiritual aspects of Debus can be seen in the rituals and mantras accompanying the performances. Practitioners often engage in spiritual preparation and meditation to achieve a high level of concentration. Special mantras are recited to seek protection from ancestral spirits or to strengthen their bodies and minds. This creates a sacred atmosphere, infusing Debus performances with profound spiritual dimensions. It's essential to note that Debus also carries social and cultural values. Debus practitioners are often respected in Bantenese society as local heroes and tradition keepers. They also serve as spiritual leaders guiding the community in daily life. While Debus has strong traditional roots, it is not static and continues to evolve over time. Some Debus practitioners have modernized the art by incorporating contemporary elements, such as electronic music or modern stage design, to attract the attention of younger generations and ensure the sustainability of this cultural heritage. In a broader context, Debus is part of efforts to preserve and promote local culture in Indonesia. The government and local communities actively support the preservation of this art as a valuable cultural heritage. Thus, Debus is not just a local martial art but also a symbol of Indonesia's cultural richness that needs to be safeguarded for future generations.",
