        "desc2eng": "Rambu Solo involves various traditional ceremonies held sequentially. These ceremonies include the sacrifice of livestock, offering of offerings, and other traditional rituals. Each stage has symbolic meanings and a strong concept of life after death. One of the most striking elements of Rambu Solo is the tau-tau. Tau-tau are wooden statues representing the spirits of the deceased. These statues are placed in graves and believed to be the dwelling place of ancestral spirits. Tau-tau are often adorned with clothing and Toraja-specific accessories that reflect the social status and wealth of the deceased. A well-bathed and decorated body is placed in a unique coffin. The funeral procession involves the journey of the deceased towards the graves located on cliffs or caves designated for the family. The funeral is often accompanied by traditional songs and dances. Rambu Solo has strict traditional rules, including the division of tasks and responsibilities among family members, adherence to customs during the ceremony, and communication protocols with ancestral spirits. The continuity of this tradition is crucial for the Toraja community, and they believe that violating customs can bring disaster. Rambu Solo is not just a physical death procession; it also holds deep spiritual meaning. The Toraja people believe that ancestral spirits remain around them and can bring blessings or misfortune depending on how they are treated. Rambu Solo also becomes a significant moment to strengthen social bonds within the Toraja community. It is not just a one-time event but passes on life values and beliefs to the next generation. This procession involves the participation of many family members and the community, creating strong bonds between individuals and the community.",
